07230nam a22006855i 9780773559813DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735598137 a10.1515/97807735598132doi  a(DE-B1597)654741  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9184.3b.C365 2019 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a810.997107222300aCanLit Across Media :bUnarchiving the Literary Event /ced. by Katherine McLeod, Jason Camlot. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b13 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Unarchiving the Literary Event -- tArchives of Canadian Cultural Production -- tCBC Radio’s Digital Archives and the Production of Canadian Citizenship and Culture -- tOthertalk: Conversational Events in the Roy Kiyooka Digital Audio Archive -- tPoetry on TV: Unarchiving Phyllis Webb’s CBC-TV Program, Extension (1967) -- tCanadian Pulp Fictions: Unarchiving Genre Fiction as CanLit -- tVoices Kept in Context: Underpinning and Not Unpinning the Recordings Found in Literary Archives -- tArchival Lacunae and the Mediated Event -- tArchival Spectres and Formats of the Event: The Foster Poetry Conference, 1963 -- t“It’s All a Curious Dream”: Nostalgia, Old Media, and the Vancouver Poetry Conference, 1963 -- tLinguistic Therapy c. 1973: Archival Traces from Véhicule’s Press -- tListening to the Unscripted: Aura and Experience in Irving Layton’s Televisual Archives -- tTraces of a Feminist Literary Event: Women and Words, 1983 -- tSalvage Modernisms: Indigenous Knowledges, Digital Repatriation, and Reconciliation -- tArchives of the Present -- tIs the TRC a Text? -- tThe Material of Palinodic Time: Sounding the Voice of Lisa Robertson’s Archival Poetics -- tUnfolding Echoes: Temporal Frames and Resituated Archives in Digital Poetics -- tExcerpt from an Audio Recording: (from a presentation at the TransCanada conference at the University of Toronto) -- tThe Archive in Motion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe materials we turn to for the construction of our literary pasts - the texts, performances, and discussions selected for storage and cataloguing in archives - shape what we know and teach about literature today. The ways in which archival materials have been structured into forms of preservation, in turn, impact their transference and transformation into new forms of presentation and re-presentation. Exploring the production of culture through and outside of the archives that preserve and produce CanLit as an entity, CanLit Across Media asserts that CanLit arises from acts of archival, critical, and creative analysis. Each chapter investigates, challenges, and provokes this premise by examining methods of "unarchiving" Canadian and Indigenous literary texts and events from the 1950s to the present. Engaging with a remediated archive, or "unarchiving," allows the authors and editors to uncover how the materials that document past acts of literary production are transformed into new forms and experiences in the present. The chapters consider literature and literary events that occurred before live audiences or were broadcast, and that are now recorded in print publications and documents, drawings, photographs, flat disc records, magnetic tape, film, videotape, and digitized files. Showcasing the range of methods and theories researchers use to engage with these materials, CanLit Across Media reanimates archives of cultural meaning and literary performance. Contributors include Jordan Abel (University of Alberta), Andrea Beverley (Mount Allison University), Clint Burnham (Simon Fraser University), Jason Camlot (Concordia University), Joel Deshaye (Memorial University of Newfoundland), Deanna Fong (Simon Fraser University), Catherine Hobbs (Library and Archives Canada), Dean Irvine (Agile Humanities), Karl Jirgens (University of Windsor), Marcelle Kosman (University of Alberta), Jessi MacEachern (Concordia University), Katherine McLeod (Concordia University), Linda Morra (Bishop's University), Karis Shearer (University of British Columbia, Okanagan), Felicity Tayler (University of Ottawa), and Darren Wershler (Concordia University).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchival materialszCanada. 0aCanadian literaturexArchival resources. 0aCanadian literaturexResearchxMethodology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Jordan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeverley, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnham, Clint, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamlot, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamlot, Jason, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDeshaye, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFong, Deanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHobbs, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrvine, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJirgens, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosman, Mmarcelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaceachern, Jessi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLeod, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLeod, Katherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aM